{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17612781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17612781"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:27:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:27:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16284"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16284"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0.07,0,0.68,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8975"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115504"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8975","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8975"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16284"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97507"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5586"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"},{"type":"tags","id":"7550"},{"type":"tags","id":"7552"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21355"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21359"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22681"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115504","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/115504"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe extraocular muscles work in coordinated pairs to produce smooth eye movements. Different combinations of muscles are responsible for specific directions of gaze.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA particular pair of muscles work together to elevate the eye in the primary position.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is that pair of muscles?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Inferior rectus and inferior oblique","Medial rectus and inferior oblique","Medial and lateral rectus","Superior rectus and inferior oblique","Superior rectus and superior oblique"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior rectus and inferior oblique muscles\u003C/strong\u003E work together synergistically to elevate the eye in the primary position. The superior rectus has its primary action of elevation but also produces intorsion and adduction. The inferior oblique counteracts these secondary actions while contributing to elevation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial rectus and inferior oblique\u003C/strong\u003E combination would produce adduction with elevation and extorsion, while the \u003Cstrong\u003Esuperior rectus and superior oblique\u003C/strong\u003E would produce elevation with excessive intorsion. The \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial and lateral rectus\u003C/strong\u003E muscles are horizontal movers and do not contribute to elevation. The \u003Cstrong\u003Einferior rectus and inferior oblique\u003C/strong\u003E work as antagonists, with the inferior rectus depressing the eye. This synergistic pairing allows for precise control of eye elevation while maintaining the eye in the primary position without unwanted torsion or horizontal deviation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The superior rectus and inferior oblique muscles work together synergistically to elevate the eye in the primary position.","The superior rectus muscle\u0027s primary action is elevation, but it also has secondary actions of intorsion and adduction.","The inferior oblique muscle\u0027s primary action is extorsion, but it also elevates and abducts the eye."],"references":["Donaldson IM. The functions of the proprioceptors of the eye muscles. Philos Trans R Soc Lond B Biol Sci. 2000 Dec 29;355(1404):1685-754. doi: 10.1098/rstb.2000.0732. PMID: 11205338; PMCID: PMC1692902.","Shumway CL, Motlagh M, Wade M. Anatomy, Head and Neck, Eye Extraocular Muscles. [Updated 2022 Oct 13]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519565/","Netter, F. H. (2015). Netter\u0027s Cranial Nerve Collection E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences.","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97507"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16284"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97507","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/97507"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-24T09:57:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-24T09:59:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8975"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"115504"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","